+Drayco Makargo
I wouldn't say it's interesting as much as a fun fan-fic. Robot Chicken did 
this first and they obviously realize it's funny because it's so absurd. 
The reason I have trouble calling it a theory is because it's kind of in 
reverse. Obviously and inarguably, Lucas let us know there are two Sith and 
presents Anakin in Phantom Menace as the one who will eventually be 
Sidious' apprentice. Given what we know from the Original Trilogy, it's a 
foregone conclusion that makes this "theory" 100% impossible. It's fun as a 
joke but these movies aren't abstract. There was clearly no intent to leave 
this up to viewer discretion. The saga tells a straightforward narrative in 
which Jar Jar being Sith just isn't the case. I'm reminded of Bladerunner 
and Dark Knight Rises. Both these movies have endings that aren't 100% 
spelled out. That being said, there is not only enough to lead a careful 
viewer to the conclusions that Deckard is a replicant and Bruce Wayne 
lived, but in fact the directors confirm as much. There can be no competing 
theories on these facts, but there can be endless fan-fic and what-ifs. 
That's what we have with the Jar Jar thing. It's a fan-fic what-if, not a 
debatable theory. There are now 6 episodes since Phantom Menace which cover 
a 50 year time span and there has been no hint of the "theory" being true. 
It's just absurd to argue that until Episode 9 is released, there's still a 
chance that Snoke or someone else will just reveal themselves as Jar Jar. 
And that leads me to the other problem. It is not falsifiable to the 
conspiracy nuts. They are now starting to argue (because they know deep 
down they are wrong) that Snoke's appearance and voice and the fact that he 
will never be revealed as Jar Jar are actually proof that he definitely is. 
When a conspiracy theorist is wrong they have 2 options: admit it, or go 
deeper down the rabbit hole, insisting they are right and making the 
"theory" even more complex. The bottom line is it's been 6 episodes, 50+ 
years in universe time, 16 years in the real world, and still no sign at 
all that Jar Jar is or ever was meant to be Sith. Combine that with the 
blatant lies of the theory's strongest supporters and there is only one 
logical conclusion to be reached.

Sure. It was just like Kirshner talking about Yoda in Empire Strikes Back. 
If the effect wasn't realistic, it would take you out of the film and you'd 
have Luke talking to a muppet. Lucas was pushing special effects forward in 
the Prequels just like he did in the Originals. He wanted to see if you 
could create a digital character that felt real when it was with the main 
cast. Instead of just taking that one little snippet of him saying "Jar Jar 
is the key," watch the whole thing and the context of it. He's clearly not 
talking about plot points, story, or the Sith (when he does, and he did 
frequently, it's always about Sidious and Anakin). The context is the 
technical aspects of the filmmaking. That's why I say it's intellectually 
dishonest to present the quote in the context of this moronic theory. There 
is so much that is taken out of context, intentionally misleading, or 
outright lie that the so-called theory doesn't merit being taken seriously.
